Bug.WithStack:
Build: 200303272130

When I converted the inner type below to a top level type, the refactoring tool
added a parameter to "this" that is not needed in the converted type. The new
constructor looked like this:
	public JavaSearchResultCollector(EvaEditionCreator creator,
                                         List foundTypes, IProgressMonitor pm) {
		this.progressMonitor = pm;
		this.collector = creator;
		this.foundElements = foundTypes;
	}


I had to delete this parameter manually. This relates to my feature request
https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=38226


	private class JavaSearchResultCollector
		implements IJavaSearchResultCollector {

		private IProgressMonitor progressMonitor;
		private List foundTypes;

		public JavaSearchResultCollector(List foundTypes,
                                                 IProgressMonitor pm) {
			this.progressMonitor = pm;
			this.foundTypes = foundTypes;
		}

		public void accept(
			IResource resource,
			int start,
			int end,
			IJavaElement enclosingElement,
			int accuracy)
			throws CoreException {
			if (foundTypes != null) {
				// kick out anonymous inner classes - they are found as methods
				if (enclosingElement.getElementType() == IJavaElement.TYPE) {
					foundTypes.add(enclosingElement);
				}
			}
		}

		public IProgressMonitor getProgressMonitor() {
			return progressMonitor;
		}

		public void done() {
		}

		public void aboutToStart() {
		}
	}
Perhaps it's personal preference, but I think "this" qualifications on fields in
constructors are good because they avoid the common bug of assigning parameters
to themselves.  However, there are other cases where this refactoring adds
"this" to method invocations, which is definitely not needed. See bug 38114 for
another example.


This is not exactly what I meant. I like the "this" qualifier as well. What I
don't like is that the refactoring introduces a new parameter to call the
constructor:

Before refactoring:
public JavaSearchResultCollector(List foundTypes,
                                 IProgressMonitor pm) {

After refactoring:
public JavaSearchResultCollector(EvaEditionCreator creator,
                                 List foundTypes,
                                 IProgressMonitor pm) {

The "creator" parameter is what I don't like. OK. The documentation states that
the refactoring is designed to add this back reference. So we might have a
feature request instead of a bug report.
Adam, please comment.
if the member type is static, then no 'back pointer' is needed and none is added
otherwise, the refactoring always adds it, although it's not always needed
(it's needed only when the member type accesses members from the enclosing 
instance)

so this report is really a feature request for detecting the case where a 
nested type could be declared static (btw. there should be something that 
detects that - having non static member types, when they can be static, is bad 
style) and not add the pointer to the enclosing instance in that case

adapting severity accordingly
please comment if i misunderstood


