Bug.WithStack:
It appears that on Windows the Table class always allocates a small border,
with a width equal to the value of OS.GetSystemMetrics (OS.SM_CXEDGE), 
whether you explicitly set a border or not. If you don't set a border then 
the actual physical border is equal to this value. If you set a border 
then this value has to be added to the reported value.

The current implementation of getBorderWidth(), inherited from the Control
class, doesn't take this into account. This results id that the preferred 
size of the Table is being slightly underestimated, which causes unwanted 
scrollbars. 

Here's a test case that shows the problem:

    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        Display display = new Display();
        Shell shell = new Shell(display);
        shell.setText("Broken Table Border?");

        Table table = null;

        String mode = args[0];
        if("current".equals(mode))
        {
          // this will have an unwanted vertical scrollbar
          table = new Table(shell, SWT.NONE);
        }
        else if("proposed_noborder".equals(mode))
        {
          table = new ProposedFixTable(shell, SWT.NONE);
        }
        else if("proposed_border".equals(mode))
        {
          table = new ProposedFixTable(shell, SWT.BORDER);
        }

        new TableItem(table,SWT.NONE).setText("ReallyReallyLongTableItem1");
        new TableItem(table,SWT.NONE).setText("ReallyReallyLongTableItem2");
        new TableItem(table,SWT.NONE).setText("ReallyReallyLongTableItem3");

        table.setSize(table.computeSize(100, SWT.DEFAULT));

        shell.pack();
        shell.open();

        while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
            if (!display.readAndDispatch())
                display.sleep();
        }
        display.dispose();

    }

    static public class ProposedFixTable extends Table
    {

      public ProposedFixTable(Composite parent, int style)
      {
        super(parent, style);
      }

      protected void checkSubclass () {}

      public int getBorderWidth ()
      {
        int borderWidth = super.getBorderWidth();
        borderWidth += OS.GetSystemMetrics (OS.SM_CXEDGE)/2;
        return borderWidth;
      }
    }
Doesn't seem like the right fix to lie about border width so it can be called 
from computeSize() (unless of course, the actual physical border, when 
measured with a pixel measuring tool is "super.getBorderWidth + 
OS.GetSystemMetrics (OS.SM_CXEDGE)/2" pixels wide)

OS.GetSystemMetrics (OS.SM_CXEDGE)/2; doesn't work for some xp theme 
like 'plus! da vinci'.



I've dug a little deeper into this problem and think I understand it now.
Not sure what the correct fix is though.

Take a table with a border, 3 rows and a horizontal scrollbar. Also, set
the lines visible. The height returned by this call in the computeSize
method:

OS.SendMessage (handle, OS.LVM_APPROXIMATEVIEWRECT, -1, bits);

is 58. By taking a screen capture and blowing up the pixels I found that
the scrollbar is 16 pixels high. The table item height is reported as 14
pixels, so this 58 must be 3*14 + 16 = 58. The table computeSize method
adds 2*border to the height, where border is reported as 2 pixels (which
is correct for a raised border, as confirmed by examining the screen 
capture). So, the preferred height, as returned by computeSize, is 62 
pixels. However, setting the table to this height gives an unwanted 
vertical scrollbar. By experimentation I found that adding 2 pixels to 
the height got rid of the scrollbar, and now I think I understand why.

If you examine the screen capture you'll see that there's a single pixel
high line above the topmost row. I don't know why it's there, but this 
accounts for 1 extra pixel. The other extra pixel is needed to show the
bottom line of the bottom row. This is the old fence/fencepost issue. 
The actual interior pixels of a row, by examination of the screen capture, 
is 13 pixels. Each row has space for a single pixel line at top and bottom.
The row height reported  by the table is 14 pixels, interior plus top, 
or bottom, line. The height of n rows is therefore 14*n + 1, not 14*n.
So, the correct height is:

 1(extra top line) + (14*3 + 1)(rows) + 16(h_scroll) + 2*2(border) = 64

Setting the height to this value gets rid of the scrollbar.

The reason I proposed adding OS.GetSystemMetrics (OS.SM_CXEDGE) was that
even when no border is set this call returns 2, which is the number of 
missing pixels. Maybe this is just coincidence. Also, I'm sure that all
of these calculations go out of the window when you use certain XP themes.
So, not sure what the correct general fix is, but it was fun getting to 
the bottom of the problem.





Created attachment 5016
Screen capture of table

This screen capture of a table with no scrollbars (height set with 2 extra
pixels added) illustrates the issues I described in my previous comment.
I see. But in your test case the computeSize of Table is not including the 16 
pixels of the scrollbar cause the hHint is different than SWT.DEFAULT. Look at 
the implementation of computeSize, at end:
if (((style & SWT.H_SCROLL) != 0) && (hHint != SWT.DEFAULT)) {
	height += OS.GetSystemMetrics (OS.SM_CYHSCROLL);
}
This code fails cause the hHint used is not wide enough and force the 
horizontal scrollbar to show. But the scrollbar height is not included in the 
total height.

Note: LVM_APPROXIMATEVIEWRECT does not consider the space for the vertical 
scrol (as it says in the java comment at end of computeSize).
it returns: (numberOfItems * itemHeight) + (itemHeight + 2).

this can be verified by setting different fonts (with different height) in the 
table and running the test case.

