VI to investigate.

NOTE: The API setParent is not supported on all platforms.

There are currently many limitations of the setParent API.  The fact that 
child shells do not get reparented properly is what is being demonstrated here.

The fix is to create the popup shell just before it is to be shown and destroy 
it when it closes.  This will solve the reparenting problem.
If we fix in this manner than we need to face some other problem.Because This 
use the list in most fns.If we dispose it it will crate some other problem.

Can u give me the full details abt your fix?
Please feel free to modify the Severity of the bug report but the Priority is 
used by the development team only.
Creating the popup shell every time is a pain becuase it means we can't use 
the OS to store things such as the item list or the selection.

Reparenting the shell just before opening it is not a good solution because 
the popup Shell will be disposed if the old parent shell gets disposed at any 
time prior to shoowing the list (e.g. create CCombo in shell_1 and then 
reparent to shell_2.  Dispose shell1 without popping down the list.  Then when 
you try to display the list you geta Widget is Disposed error.)

I think the best solution right now is to create the popup Shell with no 
parent (popup = new Shell(display, SWT.NO_TRIM)).  The problem with this 
solution is that the popup shell will appear in the task bar on Windows.

I am requesting that when a shell is created with the style SWT.NO_TRIM then 
it should not appear in the task bar (on all platforms).  When this is 
provided, I will be able to fix this bug.

See bug 40420.
Fixed.  The popup is created as a top level shell with the ON_TOP style.

popup = new Shell (getDisplay(), SWT.NO_TRIM | SWT.ON_TOP);
This fix caused problems when CCombo appeared in modal dialogs. See bug 65697.

For 3.0 RC2 a different fix has been implemented.
For 3.0 RC2 a different fix has been implemented.

